Image.OriginalCaption: The Air Operations Department, with it's seven divisions, performs a variety of tasks, without which the Station could not be run efficiently. The departments duties include flight support and scheduling, air traffic control; crash and salvage operations; maintenance of arresting gear; dockside services for Alameda's five aircraft carriers and other ships; aircraft, electronic and communications equipment maintenance; shooting and processing of aerial photography; and structural fire protection. The Air Operations Officers office is located in Building 19, the Air Operation's Building on Nimitz Field. Alameda Air Terminal, Building 77 is the largest Naval Air Terminal on the West Coast and is the eastern terminus of Navy trans-Pacific flights.
Image.Credit: U.S. Naval Air Station Alameda - Armed Forces Directory Service Inc.

Image.OriginalCaption: The Marine Barracks is responsible for perimeter and certain segments of internal security at the Naval Air Station. The Barracks constantly has Marine personnel available to respond to domestic or internal disturbances; provides honor guards for visiting dignitaries; furnishes color guards as required; assists in emergencies of all types or to establish and phase of security as requested by the Commanding Officer. Through an effective training program all Marine Barracks personnel maintain a consistently high level of combat readiness for eventual duty as an integral part of the Fleet Marine Force.
Image.Credit: U.S. Naval Air Station Alameda - Armed Forces Directory Service Inc.

Image.OriginalCaption: The Dental Department provides complete dental services for all military personnel based at Naval Air Station, Alameda. It has an extensive preventative dentistry program for military personnel and extends this program on a year-round basis for dependent children aged six to eighteen years of age.
Image.Credit: U.S. Naval Air Station Alameda - Armed Forces Directory Service Inc.

Image.OriginalCaption: The Aircraft Intermediate Maintenance Department at the Naval Air Station, Alameda, is responsible for support of all tenant squadrons, both USN and USNR, in equipment qualification; off equipment repair; and repair or replacement of damaged or unserviceable parts, components or assemblies. They also are capable of the manufacture of non-available parts and providing technical assistance to the using organization. In accomplishing these tasks, AIMD is processing an average of 5,000 components per month.
Image.Credit: U.S. Naval Air Station Alameda - Armed Forces Directory Service Inc.

Image.OriginalCaption: Fleet Tactical Support Squadron THIRTY (VR-30) was commissioned on October 1, 1966 and is based at the Naval Air Station, Alameda. In carrying out it's mission, VR-30 provides aerial logistic support for Fleet units and squadrons throughout the continental United States, airlifting special weapons, priority personnel, and material from shore bases to the aircraft carriers of the Pacific Fleet. In addition, the squadron transports passengers and cargo to land bases throughout the western United States on an around-the-clock basis. The squadron flies the Douglas C-9B "Skytrain II", the Grumman C-1A "Trader", the North American Rockwell CT-39 "Sabreliner", and the Convair C-131F, which is being pased out at this time (1974). VR-30 has provided astronaut and VIP transportation between recovery carriers and land stations for Appollos 8, 11, 12, 16 and 17. During Appollos 11 and 12, the squadron transported Moon samples from the carrier Hornet to the island of Samoa. For Apollo 16, VR-30 transported Astronauts Young, Duke and Mattingly to Hawaii from the recovery ship in addition to transporting Moon samples. The Alameda based squadron is also charged with the task of training all aircraft carrier transport pilots for the Pacfic Fleet.
Image.Credit: U.S. Naval Air Station Alameda - Armed Forces Directory Service Inc.

Image.Title: Electronic System Repair
Image.OriginalCaption: Component Program - Over one and a half million labor hours are devoted annually to processing 80,000 components. These are aircraft, missile and engine sub-assemblies that support the fleet via the Aviation Supply Office. The extensive facilities supporting components include versatile numerically controlled machine tools, automatic electronic test systems, plating, heat treating, stripping, hydraulic testing, foundry, ordnance testing, rubber manufacture, bearing repair, and an extensive variety of other equipment.
Image.Credit: Naval Air Rework Facility (NARF) - Naval Air Station Alameda

Image.Title: Engine Rotor Buildup
Image.OriginalCaption: NARF overhauls and repairs approximately 900 major aircraft engines annually. Complete disassembly, cleaning, non-destructive test, N/C machining, plating, metal spray, welding, assembly and test facilities are provided for a wide variety of jet, turbo jet, and turbo fan engines. The fully instrumented test cells are capable of handling up to 30,000 pounds thrust. Currently, primary programs include rework of the JF52, TF30, TF34, TF41 and T56 engines for the Navy and Air Force.
Image.Credit: Naval Air Rework Facility (NARF) - Naval Air Station Alameda

Image.Title: A-6 Intruder Aircraft Line
Image.OriginalCaption: Aircraft Program - About 150 aircraft undergo rework at the Facility each year. Depot level maintenance is performed on the A-3 Sky Warrior, A-6 Intruder, P-3 Orion, S-3 Viking and other miscellanous aircraft as required. The Facility provides a complete range of production (strip, fabrication, structural repair, test, etc.) and engineering (aeronautical, chemical, analytical, etc.) services to support the production line. Its spacious high bay hangars can accomodate all aircraft in the naval inventory.
Image.Credit: Naval Air Rework Facility (NARF) - Naval Air Station Alameda

Image.Title: Automated Electronic Test
Image.OriginalCaption: Other Support Programs - This is the most diversified segment of NARF's workload and provides and excellent measure of the Alameda Station's capabilities and flexibility. Engineering support, manufacturing, N/C programming, automatic test equipment, programming, aeronatical field teams, fleet training, on-board ship support, preservation, electronic calibration and standards calibration are just a few of the sub-programs supported at Alameda.
Image.Credit: Naval Air Rework Facility (NARF) - Naval Air Station Alameda

Image.Title: Shrike Missile in Test
Image.OriginalCaption: Missile Program - Alameda's unique missle rework facility provides state of the art depot support for guidance and control systems on the Phoenix, Shrike and Sparrow air launched missiles. Approximately 3,000 missiles from the Navy and Air Force undergo modification or repair each year at NARF. An extensive array of sophisticated computer controlled test systems equip this versatile complex which includes a super clean room, vibration test equipment, automatic antenna test chambes and a highly skilled and technically competent pool of electronics mechanics and engineers.
Image.Credit: Naval Air Rework Facility (NARF) - Naval Air Station Alameda
